DWR diverts water under Permits 16477 and 16480 for power generation recreation and fish and wildlife Enhancement.  Maximum rate of direct diversion and diversion to storage has been reached for Permit 16477; additional time is required to maximize the total annual diversions.  Total annual diversion to storage and maximum withdrawal under Permit 16480 is expected to increase as demands within the State Water Project service area increase.  The Oroville/Thermalito complex is operated primarily for water supply purposes which are authorized under Permits 16478 and 16479.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on end of season storage, hydrology, SWP demands and regulatory constraints.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process.  Following completion of the BDCP process, DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for project water.

Construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete.  The facilities link the SWP at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete.  DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009.  Work has begun on Phase 2 with completion of major construction activities currently projected for late 2014.  Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.  

Maximum annual diversion to storage at Lake Oroville and peak rate of direct diversion authorized under Permit 16478 have been reached.  However, additional time is required to maximize the total annual diversion and beneficial use authorized under Permit 16478 and the remaining permits governing SWP operations at Oroville and in the Delta, Permits 16479, 16481, 16482 and 16483.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on numerous factors including end of season storage, annual hydrology, SWP demands and regulatory constraints.  Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension with the State Water Resources Control Board on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process.  At this time, DWR is requesting a 5 year extension to allow time for the current planning processes to be completed.  Following completion of the BDCP process DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for Project water.

Construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete.  The facilities link the SWP at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete.  DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009.  Work has begun on Phase 2 with completion of major construction activities currently projected for late 2014.  Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.  

Maximum annual diversion to storage at Lake Oroville and peak rate of direct diversion authorized under Permit 16478 have been reached.  However, additional time is required to maximize the total annual diversion and beneficial use authorized under Permit 16478 and the remaining permits governing SWP operations at Oroville and in the Delta, Permits 16479, 16481, 16482 and 16483.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on numerous factors including end of season storage, annual hydrology, SWP demands and regulatory constraints.  Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension with the State Water Resources Control Board on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process.  At this time, DWR is requesting a 5 year extension to allow time for the current planning processes to be completed.  Following completion of the BDCP process DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for Project water.

The City has filed a Petition for Extension of Time and Petitions for Changes in Point of Diversion and Place of Use with the State Water Board requesting additional time to complete both construction of the facilities necessary to make full beneficial use under the permit and to use the water authorized by the permit.

Historically, poor water quality groundwater in the Mission Basin (the San Luis Rey River) forced the City to import the majority of its supply from the San Diego County Water Authority. Currently, approximately 83% of the City’s annual customer demand is met with imported water. Waters diverted through the City’s wells is brackish (1600 mg/L tds), which requires that 80% of the City’s production is treated by reverse osmosis (desalination) and then blended for municipal use. The Mission Basin Desalter Facility (MBDF), which was constructed in 1992, has a treated water production capacity of 6.3 gpd (or approximately 7,050 afy). The City has undertaken several significant upgrades of the MBDF. In 2004, the City expanded the MBDF’s treatment capacity from 2.0 MGD to 6.4 MGD. In 2009, the City completed installation of a granular activated carbon (GAC) treatment system to remove 1, 2, 3 trichloropropane (TCP) from the source water in Wells 1, 2, 3, 9, 10 and 11. Additionally, the City has also upgraded its production and distribution system. In 2014, the City completed construction of a new 4.5 mgd booster station in order to increase the City's water flow from its “320 pressure zone” to its “511 pressure zone,” which will maintain distribution flows throughout the system. These upgrades have expanded the City’s capacity to maximize its beneficial use of water under Permit 5229. The City owns and operates 8 production wells. Currently, the City is undertaking an optimization study of its existing wells to assess whether any improvements are required to maximize the wells’ full production potential. The optimization study is in the evaluation stages and further testing will be required to determine whether additional construction will be required to maximize beneficial use of water pursuant to Permit 5229. In 2011, the City filed a Petition for Extension of Time and a Petition for Changes in Point of Diversion and Place of Use. The City’s petitions are pending.

*The date below in 6f is contingent upon the timely completion of the optimization study.

Historically, poor water quality groundwater in the Mission Basin (underflow of the San Luis Rey River) forced the City to import the majority of its supply from the San Diego County Water Authority. Currently, approximately 87% of the City’s annual customer demand is met with imported water. Waters diverted through the City’s wells is brackish (1600 mg/L total dissolved solids), which requires that 80% of the City’s production be treated by reverse osmosis (desalination) and then blended for municipal use. The Mission Basin Desalter Facility (MBDF), which was constructed in 1992, has a treated water production capacity of 6.3 gpd (or approximately 7,050 afy). The City has undertaken several significant upgrades of the MBDF. In 2004, the City expanded the MBDF’s treatment capacity from 2.0 MGD to 6.4 MGD.  In 2009, the City completed installation of a granular activated carbon (GAC) treatment system at its Mission Basin Desalter Facility in order to remove 1, 2, 3trichloropropane (TCP) from the source water in Wells 1, 2, 3, 9, 10 and 11. Additionally, the City has also upgraded its production and distribution system. In 2014, the City completed construction of a new 4.5 mgd booster station in order to increase the City's water flow from its “320 pressure zone” to its “511 pressure zone,” which will maintain distribution flows throughout the system. These upgrades have expanded the City’s capacity to maximize its beneficial use of water under Permit 5229.  The City owns and operates 8 production wells. Currently, the City is undertaking an optimization study of its existing wells to assess whether any improvements are required to maximize the wells’ full production potential. The optimization study is in the evaluation stages and further testing will be required to determine whether additional construction will be required to maximize beneficial use of water pursuant to Permit 5229. In 2011, the City filed a Petition for Extension of Time and a Petition for Changes in Point of Diversion and Place of Use. The City’s petitions are pending. Note that the date below in 6f is contingent upon the timely completion of the optimization study.

Since the mid 1990s, regulatory guidelines and requirements have limited SCVWD's ability to fully operate the Upper Penitencia Creek (Noble) diversion.  In 1994, SCVWD implemented National Marine Fisheries Service  guidelines with respect to the approach velocity for the fish screens installed at the Penitencia Creek diversion facility. In 1995, SCVWD signed a Memorandum of Understanding with the California Department of Fish and Wildlife, which required SCVWD to make a 1 cubic foot per second (cfs) bypass flow through the diversion dam at this facility at all times. In 1998, SCVWD constructed a fish ladder and revised operation for the diversion dam to maintain flow of at least 2.5 cfs through the ladder for the benefit of fish and public trust resources. In 2000, SCVWD defined a 10-year stream maintenance program (SMP) to comply with the California Environmental Quality Act and provide Endangered Species Act coverage for sediment removal during summer only and vegetation from streams as necessary to provide flood protection.  The SMP precluded removing winter blockages and maintaining the rotating drum type fish screen at the diversion on Upper Penitencia Creek.  These regulatory limitations have substantially impaired SCVWD's ability to place the full quantity of water authorized to be appropriated by direct diversion pursuant to permit 006565 to beneficial use. 

SCVWD anticipates modifying the existing diversion facility and securing the appropriate environmental permits to restore design capacity and improve reliability. This will be accomplished in conjunction with the proposed U.S. Army Corps of Engineers flood protection project on Upper Penitencia Creek, which would impact SCVWD's point of diversion under permit 006565.  The design modification will have to meet all permitting requirements guidelines including those described in the forthcoming Three Creeks Habitat Conservation Plan and Lake and Streambed Alterations Agreements, respectively.

column12:
In 1994, SCVWD implemented National Marine Fisheries Service guidelines with respect to the approach velocity for the fish screens installed at the Penitencia Creek diversion facility.  These regulatory guidelines substantially limit the capacity of the facility.

In 1995, SCVWD signed a MOU with Department of Fish and Game which requires SCVWD to make releases from the diversion dam at this facility of 1 cubic foot per second at all times.  This requirement also substantially limits SCVWD¿s to divert water.

In 1998, SCVWD constructed a fish ladder and revised operation of the diversion dam to maintain flow of at least 2.5 cfs through the ladder for the benefit of fish and public trust resources. Some flows, which previously might have been diverted to off-stream percolation, are now diverted through the fish ladder for the benefit of public trust resources and for the purpose of augmenting percolation in the streambed. 

In 2000 SCVWD defined a 10 year stream maintenance project to comply with CEQA and to obtain necessary permits to remove sediment and vegetation from streams as necessary to provide flood protection. The project description included a prohibition of in channel sediment removal work during the winter months. This has precluded removing blockages and maintaining the rotating drum type fish screen at the diversion on Upper Penitencia Creek.

Together, these regulatory limitations have substantially impaired the SCVWD¿s ability to place the full quantity of water authorized to be appropriated by direct diversion pursuant to Permit 6565 to beneficial use.  SCVWD anticipates modifying the Penitencia Creek Diversion facility to restore design capacity and improve reliability in conjunction with the Army Corps of Engineer flood control project described herein.  These improvements will be made in a manner that permits the full beneficial use under this right, while complying with NMFS and DFG regulatory guidelines.

The District requested licensing in February, 2006

In 2008, CDFG notified the District that it was in the process of replacing existing MOUs with new Streambed Alteration Agreements and that CDFG intended to terminate MOUs with the District effective December 31, 2008.  A new  Streambed Alteration Agreement has not been obtained for the diversion at upper Penitencia Creek. 

The District¿s beneficial use of water pursuant to Permit 6565 has been reduced in recent years as a result of regulatory conditions imposed on the District¿s operations for the purpose of protecting fish and wildlife.  Without reconfiguration of the diversion facility, these conditions impair the District¿s ability to increase its appropriations for authorized beneficial uses of water.   SCVWD anticipates modifying the existing diversion facility to restore design capacity and improve reliability. This will be accomplished in conjunction with the Army Corps of Engineers¿ proposed flood control project for Upper Penitencia Creek which would impact SCVWD¿s point of diversion under Permit 6565.  (The Corps¿ 1995 Reconnaissance Report recommended moving forward with the project.)  In 2001, the Corps approved an application by the District for a Section 104 General Credit for Flood Protection on Reach 1.  The District retained consultants to design the first section of the Flood Control Project. In 2003, District staff continued to collaborate with the Corps, City of San Jose (Environmental Services Department, Public Works, Planning, Parks and Recreation, Real Estate), NOAA Fisheries, Regional Water Quality Control, Department of Fish and Game, Environmental Protection Agency, Guadalupe-Coyote Resource Conservation District (GCRCD), and the Watershed Management Initiative to address issues that had arisen. Currently the project is funded through the planning phase. Timing of construction is yet to be determined.

United States Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook Public Utilities District completed Environmental Review of the Santa Margarita River Conjunctive Use Project (CUP) in 2016.  Consultation with USFWS and NMFS was also completed in 2016.  Significant effort was expended in 2016 to complete final design drawings and specifications of the Santa Margarita River CUP and award the construction contract.  The CUP final design was completed in mid-2016 and construction contract award occurred in fall 2016.  Construction activities related to the diversion facility began in mid-2017.  Construction is expected to require 2 ½ to 3 years to complete.

column12:
Despite diligent pursuit of engineering feasibility, and NEPA-CEQA environmental impact reviews, construction of the proposed project is not anticipated to start until October 1, 2014 (Federal Fiscal Year 2015) and must be complete by March 30, 2019.  As soon as the documents are available, the Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents will be made available to Board and staff for review to help support SWRCB decision-making process upon completion and/or during the public review process. 

Based on comments received through SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, Reclamation has engaged NOAA Fisheries, Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook in a design review process to identify alternative(s) that could lessen overall project impacts.  The new alternative(s) require additional engineering design work and supplemental field surveys for the environmental impact assessment including new hydrology modeling and a modified Thompson in-stream flow incremental methodology assessment.  The partners are focused on completing the Project¿s Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents.  Upon completion of the public review process and incorporation of comment-response(s), the NEPA-CEQA documents will be prepared by Camp Pendleton and Reclamation for a Record of Decision, and by Fallbrook for a Notice of Determination.

column6: Since the SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, a new alternative is part of the EIS/R process to avoid and/or minimize impacts to listed species.  A draft feasibility study has been completed on the new alternative but requires a a final peer review process before being considered final.  This peer review is scheduled for late June 2012.  Reclamation, MCBCP and FPUD have met twice with NOAA fisheries including a complete field site visit.  Two contractors have been retained to complete hydrology modeling, steelhead assessments, and draft fish passageway design review.  A second draft report incorporating additional fieldwork and modeling is slated for delivery in mid-June 2012.  The EIR/S document process is moving forward but will require this draft report before any public notice can occur.

Project Completion: On December 15, 2010 the City requested that licenses be issued on this water right permit and the companion permit at the same point of diversion. These two permits provide essential municipal supply for the City. Petitions to extend time were also filed in December 2010 for the following reason. The City believes that it has developed reasonable and benefical use under the permits that will suffice for its municipal water supply needs, in combination with its other sources of supply. However, this surface water supply is a critical element of its municipal water supply portfolio. If licenses are not issued in sufficient amount and rates, the City will need to pursue the petitions to extend time.

We are working on finalizing the Engineering, Design, and Construction report and appropriate Federal and State environmental compliance documentation.

The Santa Margarita River Conjunctive Use Project has not been built.  The project partners (Reclamation, Fallbrook Public Utility District, and Camp Pendleton) are working to finalize all appropriate documentation to move this project forward. Once constructed water use will be reported.

During this reporting period, Reclamation, Camp Pendleton, and Fallbrook completed substantial progress towards the required environmental, engineering and economic analyses.  Fallbrook and Camp Pendleton reached an agreement on a fair share of the water and costs.  Once the project is built water can be diverted and put to beneficial use.

Current effort is focused on completing the environmental documentation and ESA consultations with USFWS and NMFS, obtaining Congressional appropriations to construct the project components, and court approval of the settlement agreement.  Action steps are listed in the attachment.

Current efforts are focused on completing the environmental review process, finalizing consultation with USFWS and NMFS, obtaining Congressional appropriation construction funds, and court approval of the settlement. Additional steps required to complete the proposed Project include: Submit amendments to the proposed change petitions for these water rights permits involved; SWRCB approval of the change petitions for diversion, storage, and use; Get Congressional appropriations to construct the components of the project; Get supplemental funds for Fallbrook?s components of the project; Initiate a competitive, open competitive bid process (Dept. of Navy & Fallbrook Public Utilities District); Award bid and construct the project components; Operate the project; and Put the project?s water to full, beneficial use.

United States Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook Public Utilities District completed Environmental Review of the Santa Margarita River Conjunctive Use Project (CUP) in 2016.  Consultation with USFWS and NMFS was also completed in 2016.  Significant effort was expended in 2016 to complete final design drawings and specifications of the Santa Margarita River CUP and award the construction contract.  The CUP final design was completed in mid-2016 and construction contract award occurred in fall 2016.  Construction activities related to the diversion facility began in mid-2017.  Construction is expected to require 2 ½ to 3 years to complete.

column12:
Despite diligent pursuit of engineering feasibility, and NEPA-CEQA environmental impact reviews, construction of the proposed project is not anticipated to start until October 1, 2014 (Federal Fiscal Year 2015) and must be complete by March 30, 2019.  As soon as the documents are available, the Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents will be made available to Board and staff for review to help support SWRCB decision-making process upon completion and/or during the public review process. 
Based on comments received through SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, Reclamation has engaged NOAA Fisheries, Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook in a design review process to identify alternative(s) that could lessen overall project impacts.  The new alternative(s) require additional engineering design work and supplemental field surveys for the environmental impact assessment including new hydrology modeling and a modified Thompson in-stream flow incremental methodology assessment.  The partners are focused on completing the Project¿s Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents.  Upon completion of the public review process and incorporation of comment-response(s), the NEPA-CEQA documents will be prepared by Camp Pendleton and Reclamation for a Record of Decision, and by Fallbrook for a Notice of Determination.

column6: Since the SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, a new alternative is part of the EIS/R process to avoid and/or minimize impacts to listed species.  A draft feasibility study has been completed on the new alternative but requires a final peer review process before being considered final.  This peer review is scheduled for late June 2012.  Reclamation, MCBCP and FPUD have met twice with NOAA fisheries including a complete field site visit.  Two contractors have been retained to complete hydrology modeling, steelhead assessments, and draft fish passageway design review.  A second draft report incorporating additional fieldwork and modeling is slated for delivery in mid-June 2012.  The EIR/S document process is moving forward but will require this draft report before any public notice can occur.

The district has several projects.

(1) Tracy Lakes Groundwater Recharge Project: Completed in December of 2015,  operated in December 2016. The District will divert 3,000 acre-feet per year into Tracy Lake to provide surface water for agricultural use and groundwater recharge/

(2) South System Pump Station Replacement: The District has $1.75 million settlement from EBMUD to replace an existing pump station. This project is out to bid and permits are pending in 2017.

(3) South System Pipeline Project: The district is in the planning phases for a project to slipline its existing cast-in-place concrete pipeline with PVC that will allow the District to make pressurized deliveries to growers. The District has applied for a Bureau of Reclamation grant seeking $1 million, and is in the process of applying for a Department of Water Resources grant for $3 million. 

(4) The District is in early planning stages for projects to rehabilitate its North Diversion and pipeline system.

(5) The District entered into a transfer agreement with the City of Lodi.

The district has several on-going projects: 

(1) Tracy Lakes Groundwater Recharge Project: District-owned component completed in December of 2015. Due to flooding and high water conditions during water year 2017, the new pump station was not operable and landowner facilities necessary to re-divert water made available from this project could not completed. Once the landowner facilities are completed, the District will divert 3,000 acre feet per year into Tracy Lake to provide surface water for agricultural use and groundwater recharge.

(2) South System Pump Station Replacement: The District has $1.75 million settlement from EBMUD to replace an existing district-owned pump station. The final permit to for this project was received in March 2018 and a construction contract for this project is in place. The District is in the process of finalizing the funding component of this project. 

(3) South System Pipeline Project: The district is currently working with landowners to explore funding options for improving the pipeline and related infrastructure to deliver more surface water.  The district was unable to operate the system during most of 2017 due to flooding along the river.  The district did conduct a test run in October 2017. 

(4) The District is in early planning stages for projects to rehabilitate its North Diversion and pipeline system. 

(5) The District completed a pilot recharge project by flooding vineyard post-harvest, in cooperation with Sustainable Conservation.  The results were very promising and the district is continuing to work with Sustainable Conservation to expand the project concept. 

(6) The District sold water to the City of Lodi in 2017 pursuant to a transfer agreement.

The District has requested an extension of time through 2025 which has not been acted upon by the board as of the submittal of this report.  The District is working to expand water use from its existing diversion structures and has recently formed an improvement district to fund a new diversion for the Tracy Lake Recharge Project, for which the District plans to submit the required change petitions shortly.

The District has requested an extension of time through 2025 which has not been acted upon by the board as of the submittal of this report.  The District is working to expand water use from its existing diversion structures and has formed an improvement district to fund a new diversion for the Tracy Lake Recharge Project, for which the district plans to submit the required change petitions shortly.

Diversions during the winter months are currently limited by temporary restrictions placed on the use of this source by the California Department of Health Services. The city completed construction of a treatment facility to eliminate this seasonal restriction in 2005. Plans to construct a pipeline to the new treatment facility have been reconsidered. A treatment facility at this location is being considered. The city filed a timely petition for extension of time on November 4, 2002. The City is currently drafting a petition for extension of time.

Diversions are limited by CDPH Groundwater Under the Direct Influence of Surface Water regulations. The City is not permitted to utilize water right A013217 during the wet months, unless it can treat the water to CDPH permitted standards. The City completed the construction of a water treatment plant in 2005. Plans to direct water right A013217 to the treatment facility are currently under review. The City intends to have a solution to beneficially utilize the maximum water right by 12/31/2016.

Diversions are limited by CDPH Groundwater Under the Direct Influence of Surface Water regulations. The City is not permitted to utilize water right A013217during the wet months, unless it can treat to CDPH permitted standards. The City completed construction of a water treatment plant in 2005. Plans to direct water right A013217 to the treatment facility are currently under review. The City intends to have a solution to beneficially utilize the maximum water right by 12/31/2016. Also, the City has projected full build out demand of 3562 acre-feet per year by 2030, and a petition for an extension of time has been filed but not yet resolved.

Diversions are limited by SWRCB DDW Groundwater Under the Direct Influence of Surface Water regulations. The City is not permitted to utilize water right A013217 during the wet months, unless it can treat to SWRCB DDW permitted standards. The City completed construction of a water treatment plant in 2005. Plans to direct water right A013217 to the treatment facility are currently under review, as well as investigation of options for an additional treatment plant closer to the water right POD. The City intends to have a solution to beneficially utilize the maximum water right by 12/31/2020. Also, the City has projected full build out demand of 3474 afy by 2040.

Cal Water currently operates two diversions (Upper Diversion and Station 3) on Bear Gulch Creek in concert.  Upgrades to both the water diversion facilities are ongoing.  A fish passage facility is planned for the Upper Diversion (Permit 8816).  A geotechnical analysis has been performed and the engineering design for the project is underway.  Other permitting is also taking place.  The goal is to complete construction in the summer of 2015.  Construction to upgrade the pumps at Station 3 (License 5441)is also planned for this next year.  Later, a parallel pipe will be constructed so that the diversions can be operated independently.  These improvements will allow Cal Water to divert water in accordance witht he bypass flows as agreed to in the Biological Opinion negotiated with NOAA NMFS and California Department of Fisj and Wildlife Services.  Incremental improvements may be made in the future as needed to maintain and enhance the operation of the diversion facilities.

The goal is to complete construction in the summer of 2016. Construction to upgrade the pumps at Station 3 (License 5441) is complete. These improvements will allow Cal Water to divert water in accordance with the bypass flow as agreed to in the Biological Opinion negotiated with NOAA NMFS and California Department of Fish and Wildlife Services. Construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete.  The facilities link the SWP at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete.  DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009.  Work has begun on Phase 2 with completion of major construction activities currently projected for late 2014.  Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.  

	Maximum annual diversion to storage at Lake Oroville and peak rate of direct diversion authorized under Permit 16478 have been reached.  However, additional time is required to maximize the total annual diversion and beneficial use authorized under Permit 16478 and the remaining permits governing SWP operations at Oroville and in the Delta, Permits 16479, 16481, 16482 and 16483.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on numerous factors including end of season storage, annual hydrology, SWP demands and regulatory constraints.  Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension with the State Water Resources Control Board on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process.  Following completion of the BDCP process DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for Project water.

Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension with the SWRCB on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process, currently California WaterFix (CWF) and EcoRestore. Following completion of the CWF process DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for Project water.  DWR filed a joint Petition for Change with the Bureau of Reclamation to add three new points of diversion in the north Delta to allow the construction of the CWF facilities.  In addition to the proposed CWF facilities, construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete. The facilities link the SWP at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete. DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009. Work has begun on Phase 2 with completion of major construction activities currently projected for mid-2017. Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.

The South Bay Aqueduct (SBA) and Del Valle Reservoir (DVR) have been operating together since 1969. Zone 7's two treatment plants currently treat and deliver water diverted to storage in Lake Del Valle under this permit for beneficial use. Water under this permit is also put to beneficial use through groundwater recharge activities on Arroyo Valle and Arroyo Mocho. The facilities remaining to be completed are the gravel pits (Chain of Lakes [COL]) and associated diversion structures. The COL is an area located between the cities of Pleasanton and Livermore, and refers to a series of ten mined out or active gravel quarry pits that have been or will be converted into surface water storage facilities and/or groundwater recharge basins once mining has been completed. The ten quarry pits or lakes are named Cope Lake, and Lakes A through I. Although the COL will ultimately cover approximately 2,000 acres and provide approximately 100,000 acre-feet of storage space, Zone 7 currently only owns Cope Lake and Lake I; both are not along the Arroyo Valle. Zone 7 has little to no control over quarry operations and therefore, cannot expedite their completion. Zone 7 will own the lakes once quarry operations cease. Once Zone 7 has gained access to the lakes along the Arroyo Valle, Zone 7 will be able to construct the new facilities necessary to perfect permit 111319.

This water supplies the needs of the Cal Poly State University, San Luis Obispo campus.  Implementation of the Campus Master Plan, approved by the CSU Board of Trustees, calls for growth to over 18,000 students and related faculty and staff for a population of approximately 25,000.  Details of the Master Plan include multiple new academic and support buildings in the future, as well as additional housing for over 6,300 on campus residents.  Campus has not yet reached the full build out and associated water use projected by the Master Plan.  A permit time extension was filed in 2005.

Until October of 2005, diversions during the winter months were limited by a temporary restriction placed on the use of this source by the California Department of Health Services.  The City completed construction of a treatment facility to eliminate this seasonal restriction in 2005, and year¿round diversions from this point of diversion resumed in November 2005.  Construction of a connecting pipeline bringing diversions from the City¿s other Russian River well field (Fitch Well Field, covered under A13217) to this treatment facility is scheduled to be completed by 2012.

The complete use date is listed as 12/31/2002.  The City filed a petition for extension of time on November 4, 2002.

The complete use date is listed as 12/31/2002. The City filed a timely petition for extension of time on November 4, 2002. The City is currently drafting a petition for extension of time.

Construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete.  The facilities link the SWP at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete.  DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009.  Work has begun on Phase 2 with completion of major construction activities currently projected for late 2014.  Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.  

	Maximum annual diversion to storage at Lake Oroville and peak rate of direct diversion authorized under Permit 16478 have been reached.  However, additional time is required to maximize the total annual diversion and beneficial use authorized under Permit 16478 and the remaining permits governing SWP operations at Oroville and in the Delta, Permits 16479, 16481, 16482 and 16483.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on numerous factors including end of season storage, annual hydrology, SWP demands and regulatory constraints.  Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a Petition for Time Extension with the State Water Resources Control Board on December 31, 2009.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan (BDCP) process.  Following completion of the BDCP process DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for Project water.

column12:
Construction of the East Branch Extension of the California Aqueduct is not yet complete.  The facilities link the State Water Project at the Devil Canyon power plant to the eastern part of San Bernardino Valley Water District and San Gorgonio Pass Water Agency.  Phase 1 of the East Branch Extension project is complete.  DWR certified the Final Environmental Impact Report for Phase 2 of the East Branch Extension and approved the project on March 2, 2009. The project is currently under construction.  Other facilities may be required depending on the outcome of current efforts to address issues in the Sacramento/San Joaquin Delta.  

	Maximum diversion to storage and rate of direct diversion under Permit 16478 has reached the quantities authorized under the permit.  Additional time is required to maximize beneficial use authorized under the remaining permits governing SWP operations at Oroville and in the Delta, Permits 16479, 16481 and 16482.  Annual diversions to storage are dependent on end of season storage, hydrology and State Water Project demands and regulatory constraints.  Maximum diversion rate, total annual diversion to storage and maximum annual use are expected to increase as demands within the SWP service area increase.  DWR filed a petition for time extension on December 31, 2010.  There are a number of factors creating uncertainty as to the ultimate demands for project water and the quantities available and timing of diversions including the current Bay-Delta Conservation Plan process.  At this time, DWR is requesting a 5 year extension to allow time for the current planning processes to be completed.  At that time DWR should be better able to estimate future demands for project water.

Note A: Water Right Permit 14218 BTCSD holds water right Permit 14218 (Application 21275) for diversion and storage of water at Lake Ada Rose. This permit allows direct diversion up to 0.45 cfs year-round as well as diversion to storage of up to 138 acre-feet annually during the months of September through May. Total diversion under Permit 14218 are limited to 272 acre-feet annually. No bypass for streamflow maintenance is required at Lake Ada Rose. Lake Ada Rose Reservoir is located directly above our water treatment plant. Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010) Note B. In a survey completed in February 2003 the gross capacity of the 5.6 surface acres reservoir was 138 acre-feet; net capacity was 118 acre-feet. Estimated sedimentation was 32,030 cubic yards. The top elevation of lake is 1552.6 feet above sea level. Source: T. M. Herman & Associates, Inc. (February 2003) Note C: Water Conservation Measures: Annually we ask water customers to conserve water thru the annual newsletter. The District has a water base plus water tier system in place (the more you use the higher the charge per tier increment). Additionally, the average annual water production during the 7-year period from 2003 thru 2009 was about 0.234 acre-feet per residence (76,249 gallons per year). Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010) Note D: BTCSD water use is about one-half compared to the state average for a family of four. Brooktrails is located within a redwood forest and we have very few lawns. Source: BTCSD General Manager Note E: The Watershed drainage area for Ada Rose 407 acres. The estimated watershed flow is approximately 12.7% of the USGS a streamflow gage for Willits Creek (USGS Gage #11472160) located approximately 1 mile away. Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010) Note F: In 2010 the watershed flow in the Ada Rose drainage area was 1,280 acre-feet. Source: BTCSD General Manager Note G. BTCSD has two reservoirs. Information above was only for Permit 14218. See Permit 15913 for Lake Emily Reservoir (Brooktrails 3 North Dam & Reservoir No. 1038-3) is reported independently from this report.

The Santa Margarita River Conjunctive Use Project has not been built.  The project partners (Reclamation, Fallbrook Public Utility District, and Camp Pendleton) are working to finalize all appropriate documentation to move this project forward. There is an update on its status attached. Once the project is constructed then the water benefically used will be reported.

Despite diligent pursuit of engineering feasibility design, environmental compliance and settlement negotiations, construction of the proposed project is not anticipated to start until October 1, 2015 (Federal Fiscal Year 2016). Current efforts are focused on completing the environmental review process, and obtaining Congressional appropriation of construction funds and court approval of the settlement.

Despite diligent pursuit of engineering feasibility design, environmental compliance and settlement negotiations, construction of the proposed project is not anticipated to start until October 1, 2015 (Federal Fiscal Year 2016). Current efforts are focused on completing the environmental review process, and obtaining Congressional appropriation of construction funds and court approval of the settlement.

Current effort are focused on completing the environmental documentation and ESA consultations with USFWS and NMFS, obtaining Congressional appropriations to construct the project components, and court approval of the settlement agreement. Action steps are listed in the attachment.

Current efforts are focused on completing the environmental review process, finalizing consultation with USFWS and NMFS, obtaining Congressional appropriation construction funds, and court approval of the settlement. Additional steps required to complete the proposed Project include:
Submit amendments to the proposed change petitions for these water rights permits involved; SWRCB approval of the change petitions for diversion, storage, and use; Get Congressional appropriations to construct the components of the project; Get supplemental funds for Fallbrook¿s components of the project; Initiate a competitive, open competitive bid process (Dept. of Navy & Fallbrook Public Utilities District); Award bid and construct the project components; Operate the project; and Put the project¿s water to full, beneficial use.

United States Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook Public Utilities District completed Environmental Review of the Santa Margarita River Conjunctive Use Project (CUP) in 2016.  Consultation with USFWS and NMFS was also completed in 2016.  Significant effort was expended in 2016 to complete final design drawings and specifications of the Santa Margarita River CUP and award the construction contract.  The CUP final design was completed in mid-2016 and construction contract award occurred in fall 2016.  Construction activities related to the diversion facility began in mid-2017.  Construction is expected to require 2 ½ to 3 years to complete.

column12:
Despite diligent pursuit of engineering feasibility, and NEPA-CEQA environmental impact reviews, construction of the proposed project is not anticipated to start until October 1, 2014 (Federal Fiscal Year 2015) and must be complete by March 30, 2019.  As soon as the documents are available, the Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents will be made available to Board and staff for review to help support SWRCB decision-making process upon completion and/or during the public review process. 
Based on comments received through SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, Reclamation has engaged NOAA Fisheries, Camp Pendleton and Fallbrook in a design review process to identify alternative(s) that could lessen overall project impacts.  The new alternative(s) require additional engineering design work and supplemental field surveys for the environmental impact assessment including new hydrology modeling and a modified Thompson in-stream flow incremental methodology assessment.  The partners are focused on completing the Project¿s Feasibility Study and NEPA-CEQA documents.  Upon completion of the public review process and incorporation of comment-response(s), the NEPA-CEQA documents will be prepared by Camp Pendleton and Reclamation for a Record of Decision, and by Fallbrook for a Notice of Determination.

column6: Since the SWRCB public notice of the change petitions, a new alternative is part of the EIS/R process to avoid and/or minimize impacts to listed species.  A draft feasibility study has been completed on the new alternative but requires a final peer review process before being considered final.  This peer review is scheduled for late June 2012.  Reclamation, MCBCP and FPUD have met twice with NOAA fisheries including a complete field site visit.  Two contractors have been retained to complete hydrology modeling, steelhead assessments, and draft fish passageway design review.  A second draft report incorporating additional fieldwork and modeling is slated for delivery in mid-June 2012.  The EIR/S document process is moving forward but will require this draft report before any public notice can occur.

The City of Solvang diverts water from the underflow of the Santa Ynez River using wells. The pumping capacity of the City's current wells is not sufficient to fully appropriate the quantities allowed by the City's permit. The City therefore plans to install new wells, both to increase its pumping capacity and to replace other wells that have been damaged by past flooding, in order to prove up its use under its permit. The City prepared a comprehensive "water master plan" for the City's current and future water needs and development. The wells are part of the water master plan. The City updated the water master plan in 2010 (the "Master Plan Update") and is now nearing completion of the environmental review process of the Master Plan Update. The State Water Resources Control Board has required evidence that the City has complied with the California Environmental Quality Act ("CEQA") in connection with the installation of any new wells. The City contracted with URS Corporation to prepare the City's necessary environmental documents. A Notice of Preparation was issued December 4, 2002 for a thirty-day public review period. Due to a series of delays, the internal administrative draft was issued in November of 2004 with a second draft put on hold in October 2006. The second draft was put on hold to allow for negotiation of a mutual agreement between the City and the Santa Ynex River Water Conservation District, Improvement District No. 1, regarding mitigation of additional wells drawing from the Santa Ynez River underflow. The parties have since entered into a memorandum of understanding regarding mitigation of additional wells drawing from the Santa Ynez River underflow. In early 2011, Stetson Engineers Inc. completed technical studies and modeling to develop an initial well location and pumping plan for the City to minimize any impacts to other water users. Due to modifications in the Master Plan Update, the City (through URS) issued a second Notice of Preparation for the EIR on January 4, 2011. Numerous comments were received. After many discussions between the City and URS, they made the mutual determination that the City should engage another contractor to complete the EIR. Solvang then engaged Impact Sciences, who completed the first and second administrative draft EIR. The lead biologist working on the EIR, and his team, left Impact Sciences around March 2012 to form a new firm. With the second draft EIR completed, the City decided to hire the new firm, Meridian Consultants, to complete the EIR. The City relealsed the DRaft EIR on June 15, 2012 for public comment.  The public comment period closed on July 30, 2012. The City received numerous comments and is currently finalizing its responses to comments and developing additional mitigation measures in response to those comments, which will be included in the Final EIR.

The City of Solvang diverts water from the underflow of the Santa Ynez River using wells.  The pumping capacity of the City's current wells is not sufficient to fully appropriate the quantities allowed by the City's permit.  The City, therefore, plans to install new wells, both to increase its pumping capacity and to replace other wells that have been damaged by past flooding, in order to prove up its use under its permit. The City updated its water master plan in 2010 and finalized the environmental review process in May 2014.  The State Water Resources Control Board has required evidence that the City has complied with the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) in connection with the installation of any new wells. As such, the City prepared and released a Draft EIR on July 15, 2012 for public comment.  The public comment period closed on July 30, 2012. The City prepared responses to comments and developed additional mitigation measures in response to those comments, which were included in the Final EIR.  The Final EIR was finalized in January 2014 and subsequently adopted by the City. The City is also currently preparing a petition for a Change in Reach of Diversion and a Petition for Extension of Time that will be submitted to the State Water Resources Control Board.

Examining watershed in relation to population expectations.

Note A: Water Right Permit 15913 Permit 15913 (Application 23038) allows for the direct diversion and storage of water from Willits Creek, tributary to Mill Creek, thence Outlet Creek, and thence the Eel River.1 

Permit 15913 grants the right to directly divert up to 2.3 cubic-feet per second (cfs) year round (January 1st to December 31st), not to exceed 133 af annually, and to collect to storage up to 300 af annually during the period of September 1 through June 1. Of this storage amount, 270 af may be stored at Lake Emily and 30 af may be stored in the former Summer Lake Reservoir. However, due to restrictions imposed by California Department of Fish and Game (CDFG) to protect fisheries, the Summer Lake dam is no longer used and therefore Summer Lake no longer functions as a reservoir. 

Operationally, water directly diverted and withdrawn from storage at Lake Emily is transferred to and regulated at Lake Ada Rose before it is treated at the BTCSD drinking water treatment facility adjacent to Lake Ada Rose.

In total, storage and direct diversion authorized under Permit 15913 is 433 afa [133 afa + 270 afa + 30 afa]. However, the 30 afa permitted for storage in Summer Lake has not been utilized since the reservoir was abandoned to meet CDFG requirements under the Streambed Alteration Agreement (SAA) Notification 1600-2006-0822-3 between CDFG and BTCSD, as amended (CDFG, 2007). Thus, approximately 403 afa is actually diverted over the course of the year from Lake Emily to Lake Ada Rose and then to the BTCSD drinking water facility before distribution within the BTCSD. 1. 

Per Title 23 CCR Section 658, the term "storage" means the initial collection water to fill a reservoir plus refill, in whole or in part, held for more than 30 days. Per Section 657, water diverted and held for less than 30 days is considered to be "directly diverted" or "regulated." Source: Analytical Environmental Services (September 2010)

 Note B: Water Conservation Measures: Annually we ask water customers to conserve water thru the annual newsletter. The District has a water base plus water tier system in place (the more you use the higher the charge per tier increment). Additionally, the average annual water production during the 7-year period from 2003 thru 2009 was about 0.234 acre-feet per residence (76,249 gallons per year). Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010)

Note C: BTCSD water use is about one-half compared to the state average for a family of four. Brooktrails is located within a redwood forest and we have very few lawns. Source: BTCSD General Manager 

Note D: BTCSD contracts with USGS a streamflow gage for Willits Creek a short distance above Lake Emily (USGS Gage #11472160). The Watershed drainage area for Lake Emily at diversion is 3,137 acres. Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010) 

Note E: In 2009 Lake Emily watershed flow was 3,363 acre-feet. Source: Brooktrails 2009 Water Bypass Report to CF&G. 

Note F: In 2008 BTCSD modified / expanded Lake Emily reservoir from 200 net acre-feet to 251 net acre-feet (25%) with Obermeyer gates at spillway. Lake Emily water level is 1,570.0 feet above sea level and the reservoir surface area is approximately 18 acres in size. Source: Wagner & Bonsignore Engineers (January, 2010)

 Note G: The estimated siltation in Lake Emily reservoir was 114,420 cubic yards. Source: Source: T. M. Herman & Associates, Inc. (February 2003) 

Note H: BTCSD has two reservoirs. Information above was only for Permit 15913 (Lake Emily Reservoir); for further information about water use see Permit 14218 (Lake Ada Rose Reservoir) reported independently from this report.

column12: The final step in the construction process is to complete the installation of a SCADA system, which will help the Big Rock CSD manage the water system more efficiently and beneficially.  That improvement, plus the Special District's ongoing efforts to locate and repair its leaks, will enable the Big Rock CSD to increase its place of use as noted above without increasing the diversion rate from the Smith River.  The SCADA project is approaching the final test phase.  That said, the California Department of Fish and Game has filed a frivolous protest to the Special District's proposed annexation of the Park.  The project cannot be completed until the DFG relents or California State Parks abandons its request for annexation.  The matter is well beyond the Big Rock CSD's ability to control, making it impossible to estimate a date of completion.

We have applied for a permit with California Department of Fish and Wildlife to repair a streambed that was damaged by an outflow of water from from the reservoir. We are reviewing the paperwork at this time and should have the permit within two weeks. We are also exploring the possibility of relocating the overflow channel to the north side of the dam. This will allow us to use the maximum amount of water.

We purchased the vineyard in November 2012. The property had a slump that needed to be repaired as well as issues with the location of the spillway. The slump repair was permitted mid 2013 and was completed in October of 2013. The spillway is still an issue and we are only allowed to hold up to 210 acre feet of water to ensure the spillway is not used. (permitted storage amount of water is 250 acre feet)
We are trying to determine where the new spillway can be located and how it can be designed.

Beneficial use of the water available from Houston Creek has commenced.  However, additional time is required to put the full permitted quantity to beneficial use.  The quantity of water available in Houston Creek is highly variable and is dependent on annual hydrology.  Due to the permit term requiring no net depletion to the Mojave River Drainage as a result of the authorized diversions, the Department must deliver approximately equal quantities of SWP and Houston Creek water to the Crestline-Lake Arrowhead Water Agency (CLAWA) to assure that the return flow from the combined diversions is equal to or greater than the quantity of Houston Creek water diverted.  Total demand within CLAWA must be approximately twice the quantity of Houston Creek water appropriated.  Total water use is dependent on available Houston Creek flow and population growth within CLAWA. It is anticipated that total annual water use will increase resulting in beneficial use of the full permitted quantity.

Full beneficial use will require modifications to the treatment plant to improve its capability to treat water during the fall and winter months. These improvements are planned in future years as demands necessitate. City of Napa population growth has meen much slower than originally estimated, therefore it is taking longer to develop full beneneficial use. In addition, full beneficial use has been impacted by water conservation efforts that have reduced per capita demand and will continue to do so as required by the Water Conservation Act of 2009 (SBx7-7).

The Benmore Valley Ranch is in the process of transforming agricultural operations with a 4 year plan to transition from vineyard to alfalfa, hops and orchard crops in the next 1-4 seasons as well as resuming cattle operations.  We intend to ramp up our permitted water usage to over 100 acre-feet of water as a result of these renovations.

The Benmore Valley Ranch is in active transition from commercial vineyard operations to diversified agricultural operations with an emphasis on cattle grazing.  We have removed 100 acres of vineyard and have 10 acres remaining.  Operations include cattle grazing (currently 40 head), pasture irrigation and development and orchards.   Currently we have four 40 acre fenced pastures and are actively adding infrastructure to support a comprehensive grazing program.

We are continueing to conduct research on water holding capacity of the soil system on the landscape.
The current phase includes modeling by the USGS Hydrologists, Dr.'s Alan and Lorraine Flint who are organizing the research and are producing a proposal for funding.
The potential being examined is whether increasing soil carbon will enhance the soil water holding capacity to greater amount than above ground catchment. Based on this next step, we plan to conduct small experiments with off-channel ponds and paired soil carbon amended sites to measure the difference and determine our path forward.
Please see last year's report. Same status as then

We are still actively engaged in the research of soil carbon function and the related soil moisture capacity, and are exploring alternative strategies to enjoy beneficial use of this water right such as creating multiple off-channel small ponds as well as managing the soil system for increased water holding capacity at the landscape scale.
The research is part of a larger body of work, including work being conducted by USGS Hydrologists Dr.s Alan and Lorriane Flint.

In November 2015, my family installed a screw gate as part of a larger project to prevent salt water intrusion from the Napa River. However, the family is in the middle of litigation with the County that prohibits moving forward with plans or any further design at this time. We still have plans to build a reservoir, but continuing to work with NRCS on suitable location possibilities or alternatives. The Benmore Valley Ranch is in the process of transforming agricultural 
operations with a 5 years plan to transition from vineyard, to alfalfa, 
hops and orchard crops in the next 1-5 seasons as well as resuming 
cattle operations. We intend to ramp up our permitted water usage to 
over 100 acre-feet of water as a result of these renovations.

The Benmore Valley Ranch is in the process of transforming agricultural operations with a 4 years plan to transition from vineyard to alfalfa, hops and orchard crops in the next 1-4 seasons as well as resuming cattle operations.  We intend to ramp up our permitted water usage to over 100 acre-feet as a result of these renovations.

The Benmore Valley Ranch is in active transition from commercial vineyard operations to diversified agricultural operations with an emphasis on cattle grazing.  We have removed 100 acres of vineyard and have 10 acres remaining.  Operations include cattle grazing (currently 40 head), pasture irrigation and development and orchards.   Currently we have four 40 acre fenced pastures and are actively adding infrastructure to support a comprehensive grazing program.

Permittee has filed a Petition for Change on April 12, 2015 to add 33 acres to the currently authorized 241 acres. The Petition for Change also seeks to remove proposed 49 acre-feet Reservoir #4 and replace with proposed 49 acre-feet off-stream Reservoir #8. The Petitioner also filed a Petition for Extension of Time on December 27, 2006 requesting that the authorized time to develop the project and perfect beneficial use of water be extended to December 31, 2016. As the Petition for Extension of Time is still pending approval, the Petitioner requested by letter dated April 10, 2015 that the Petition for Extension of Time be amended to allow the project to be fully developed and the full beneficial use of water to be made by December 31, 2026.

Due to health reasons in 2013 Robert Ghormley deeded the property over to his son Wesley Daniel Ghormley of Fairbanks, Alaska. Wesley comes to California to assist his elderly parents twice a year but will not be retired and permanently living back in California until late fall of 2018. Wesley plans to be proactive and submit a plan for using the water from the spring located across Hwy 49 and across from his property. He phoned Eloise Bellman from your office in 2014 to discuss property ownership changes and his future plans. Ms. Bellman assured Wesley that as long as he keeps up with the yearly progress reports and yearly fee of $150 there would not be a problem. We do not want to lose our water rights and plan to use some water in 4-5 years. Possibly for watering trees or stock. Please call me at 907-451-2164 if we need to discuss anything. Thank you. column12:
Construction of the first permitted project reservoir was completed in 2003 and filled in 2004 and diverted/stored waters are being put to permitted uses.  Construction-related activities for the second permitted project reservoir have commenced (surveying, construction bids, woodland mitigation analysis), but construction of the second-permitted reservoir is not yet complete. Bar X Trust has a petition pending before the State Water Board to extend the time to complete its construction for the second reservoir.   If the time extension request is granted, the following work will be required to complete the permitted project:

- Construct and fill the second reservoir utilizing tributary watershed rainfall and runoff, and minor diversions from Putah Creek as allowed by established riparian water right restrictions.  
- Construct outlet works, including downstream conveyance channels, and revegetate graded/disturbed areas.

In the meantime, Jackrabbit Properties, LLC continues to comply with the permit terms to include installing an maintaining all required measuring devices.

column12: During 2010 the Big Sur Land Trust continued to prepare the land for conversion back to organic agricultural operations and habitat restoration following several years of phased work for restoration of the lagoon on State Parks property and interim agricultural operations. Due to economic issues and a tightening of farm loans our agricultural producer left the property in late 2008 and the land was only minimumly farmed in 2009 and 2010. From 2009 to 2010 the Big Sur Land Trust conducted design work and assessment of the property for the grading of a permanent farm operation raised out of the 100-year floodplain as well as conversion of some portion of the land to native habitat. 60% designs are now complete and project permits have been submitted with a construction date of early Spring 2012 identified to raise the farm field out of the 100-year floodplain and complete other items such as a new farm road and some habitat restoration. During 2011 the land will be used to grow native plants and to force sprout weeds in the farmland to proactively convert some portions of the property back to native habitat through an active mowing and weeding regime. An agricultural operator will be identified this winter for the property with a date of agricultural production to be restarted in late Spring 2012.

Construction and operation of the regional wastewater reclamation facility began many years ago.  The plant has been producing recycled water for more than 10 years.  Since full operation in July 2007 to July 2014, EVMWD regularly put to beneficial use approximately 6,000 acre feet annually of the 8,400 acre feet of (recycled) water right awarded under the permit.  To complete the full use contemplated in the permit, EVWMD will have to expand its regional wastewater reclamation facility.  Because of reduced development in the service area during the last five years, expansion of the treatment plant is not expected to occur for another 5 to 11 years.  Once the treatment plant is expanded and customers connected, EVWMD expects to be able to put the full water right to use.

San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District (Valley District) and Western Municipal Water District of Riverside County (Western), (jointly, Permittees) are pursuing an aggressive program to construct the facilities needed to put the water permitted under Permit Number 21264 (Application 31165) and Permit Number 21265 (Application 31370) to beneficial use.  Permittees anticipate that they will complete the construction of the facilities by October 1, 2020.  The initial phase of work was commenced prior to June 30, 2010 and involved modification of the intake structure at the Cuttle Weir to increase the diversion rate from approximately 195 cfs to approximately 300 cfs.  Presently, Permittees are designing the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline, sedimentation basins, canal and additional recharge basins that will ultimately increase the transmission and recharge capacity to 500 cfs at the Santa Ana River recharge basins.  The first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will be constructed to deliver water to the recharge basins and to Valley District's Foothill Pipeline.  A future phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will provide added flexibility by connecting to the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California Inland Feeder.  With the completion of the first phase facilities, Permittees will be able to divert up to 500 cfs from the Santa Ana River and deliver that water: (i) for groundwater recharge into underground storage for subsequent extraction and use by the retail water agencies in the place of use under Permits 21264 and 21265, (ii) for direct deliveries to retail water agencies within the place of use though the Foothill Pipeline and/or the Inland Feeder, or (iii) some combination of (i) and (ii).  The plans for the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline and additional recharge basins are presently in draft form and additional environmental documentation is being completed. Permittees have also started acquiring additional properties necessary to construct the facilities.

San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District (Valley District) and Western Municipal Water District of Riverside County (Western), (jointly, Permittees) are pursuing an aggressive program to construct the facilities needed to put the water permitted under Permit Number 21264 (Application 31165) and Permit Number 21265 (Application 31370) to beneficial use.  Permittees anticipate that they will complete the construction of the facilities by October 1, 2020.  The initial phase of work was commenced prior to June 30, 2010 and involved modification of the intake structure at the Cuttle Weir. Permittees have completed design of the first phase of improvements that includes enhancements to the Cuttle Weir diversion, a sedimentation basin and the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline which will deliver water to the existing recharge basins and to Valley District's Foothill Pipeline. This phase could bid at the end of 2014.  The design of the second phase of the improvements is 60% complete and includes additional canal and additional recharge basins that will ultimately increase the transmission and recharge capacity to 500 cfs at the Santa Ana River recharge basins.  This phase of the improvements occurs in an environmentally sensitive area.  Environmental permitting for these improvements is being obtained through the Upper Santa Ana River Wash Land Management and Habitat Conservation Plan which is scheduled to be complete at the end of 2015.  A future phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will provide added flexibility by connecting to the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California Inland Feeder.  With the completion of the first two phases of facilities, Permittees will be able to divert up to 500 cfs from the Santa Ana River and deliver that water: (i) for groundwater recharge into underground storage for subsequent extraction and use by the retail water agencies in the place of use under Permits 21264 and 21265, (ii) for direct deliveries to retail water agencies within the place of use though the Foothill Pipeline and/or the Inland Feeder, or (iii) some combination of (i) and (ii). Permittees have also started acquiring the property necessary to construct the facilities.

A future phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will provide added flexibility by connecting to the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California Inland Feeder.  With the completion of the first phase facilities, Permittees will be able to divert up to 500 cfs from the Santa Ana River and deliver that water: (i) for groundwater recharge into underground storage for subsequent extraction and use by the retail water agencies in the place of use under Permits 21264 and 21265, (ii) for direct deliveries to retail water agencies within the place of use though the Foothill Pipeline and/or the Inland Feeder, or (iii) some combination of (i) and (ii).  The plans for the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline and additional recharge basins are presently in draft form and additional environmental documentation is being completed. Permittees have also started acquiring additional properties necessary to construct the facilities.

In addition to annual operation and maintenance work at permitted diversions and storage facilities (groundwater recharge basins) and diversion points, CY 2015 work included the development of preliminary design reports, environmental documentation and final designs on nine recharge improvement projects as proposed in the 2013 Amendment to the 2010 Recharge Master Plan Update. These nine new recharge projects are, for the most part, expansions in recharge capacities at facilities; and, construction of these proposed recharge improvements is projected to be completed in 2020.  The Chino Basin Watermaster and the Inland Empire Utilities Agency will update the recharge master plan in 2020 and every five years thereafter and they will subsequently construct additional recharge improvements to enhance diversion and recharge capacity within the quantities allowed under the three permits.

â€¢	San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District (Valley District) and Western Municipal Water District of Riverside County (Western), (jointly, Permittees) are pursuing an aggressive program to construct the facilities needed to put the water permitted under Permit Number 21264 (Application 31165) and Permit Number 21265 (Application 31370) to beneficial use.  Permittees anticipate that they will complete the construction of the facilities by October 1, 2020.  The initial phase of work was commenced prior to June 30, 2010 and involved modification of the intake structure at the Cuttle Weir. Permittees have completed design of Phase 1A of improvements that includes a sedimentation basin and the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline which will deliver water to the existing recharge basins and to Valley District's Foothill Pipeline. This phase is currently out for bid.  The design of Phase 1B is 60% complete and includes additional canal and additional recharge basins that will ultimately increase the transmission and recharge capacity to 500 cfs at the Santa Ana River recharge basins.  This phase of the improvements occurs in an environmentally sensitive area and may not commence until the environmental permitting is complete.  Environmental permitting for these improvements is being obtained through the Upper Santa Ana River Wash Land Management and Habitat Conservation Plan which is scheduled to be complete at the end of 2015 and the Upper Santa Ana River Habitat Conservation Plan which is scheduled to be complete in 2016.  A future phase, Phase 2, will connect the Plunge Pool Pipeline to the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California Inland Feeder.  With the completion of the first two phases of facilities, Permittees will be able to divert up to 500 cfs from the Santa Ana River and deliver that water: (i) for groundwater recharge into underground storage for subsequent extraction and use by the retail water agencies in the place of use under Permits 21264 and 21265, (ii) for direct deliveries to retail water agencies within the place of use though the Foothill Pipeline and/or the Inland Feeder, or (iii) some combination of (i) and (ii). Permittees have also started acquiring the property necessary to construct the facilities.

San Bernardino Valley Municipal Water District (Valley District) and Western Municipal Water District of Riverside County (Western), (jointly, Permittees) are pursuing an aggressive program to construct the facilities needed to put the water permitted under Permit Number 21264 (Application 31165) and Permit Number 21265 (Application 31370) to beneficial use.  Permittees anticipate that they will complete the construction of the facilities by October 1, 2020.  The initial phase of work was commenced prior to June 30, 2010 and involved modification of the intake structure at the Cuttle Weir to increase the diversion rate from approximately 195 cfs to approximately 300 cfs.  Presently, Permittees are designing the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline, sedimentation basins, canal and additional recharge basins that will increase the transmission and recharge capacity to 500 cfs at the Santa Ana River recharge basins.  The first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will be constructed to deliver water to the recharge basins and to Valley District's Foothill Pipeline.  A future phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline will provide added flexibility by connecting to the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California Inland Feeder.  With the completion of the first phase facilities, Permittees will be able to divert up to 500 cfs from the Santa Ana River and deliver that water: (i) for groundwater recharge into underground storage and subsequent extraction and use by the retail water agencies in the place of use of Permit 21264 and Permit 21265, (ii) for direct deliveries to retail water agencies within the place of use through the Foothill Pipeline and/or the Inland Feeder, or (iii) some combination of (i) and (ii).  The plans for the first phase of the Plunge Pool Pipeline and additional recharge basins are presently in draft form.  Additional environmental documentation is being prepared.

It is anticipated that project construction will commence in August 2013 and be completed by December 31, 2013.

Project construction began in September 2013 and construction activities are anticipated to be complete by July 2014.  After construction, some stream flow data collection, as specified in Permit 021303, is required prior to start of diversion operations.

Project construction began in September 2013 and was completed in July 2014. No water diversion has occurred yet, however, since there were terms and conditions in Permit 021303 that must be fulfilled before the start of diversion operations. The District is working toward meeting these conditions, which include collecting stream flow data to submit to NMFS and CDFW, intalling a SCADA system for remote control open/closure of the intake pipe valve, and executing an Operations Agreement with the City of San Buenaventura (completed on January 12, 2015; copy attached with this report).

Project construction was completed in July 2014. No water diversion has occurred yet, however, since there are terms and conditions in Permit 021303 that must be fulfilled before diversion operations may begin. The District is working toward meeting these conditions, which include collecting stream flow data from two "qualifying storm events" to submit to NMFS and CDFW, and installing a SCADA system for remote control open/closure of the intake pipe valve. The project has not been able to begin operations yet due to a lack of rainfall and insufficient stream flow in San Antonio Creek caused by continuing drought conditions in the region.
